# Return validators and mutation returns

## Return validators

Do not add `returns` validators to queries when the handler just returns database documents or a straightforward transformation (e.g. spreading with an extra field like `isOwner`). Return validators are only useful when you perform an adjustment that changes the shape of the data; otherwise they duplicate the schema and add maintenance without benefit.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD – return validator that only mirrors the table shape
const listReturnValidator = v.object({ _id: v.id("lists"), ... });
export const getList = query({
  args: { listId: v.id("lists") },
  returns: v.union(v.object({ ...listReturnValidator.fields, isOwner: v.boolean() }), v.null()),
  handler: async (ctx, args) => { ... },
});

// ✅ GOOD – no return validator when returning docs as-is or with simple extras
export const getList = query({
  args: { listId: v.id("lists") },
  handler: async (ctx, args) => { ... },
});
```

## Mutation returns

Do not return values from mutations. Convex queries are reactive; any subscribed query will re-run and show updated data after a mutation. Returning the created/updated document (or id) from the mutation is redundant.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD – mutation returns created id or doc
export const createList = mutation({
  args: { name: v.string() },
  handler: async (ctx, args) => {
    const id = await ctx.db.insert("lists", { ... });
    return id;
  },
});

// ✅ GOOD – mutation performs the write only
export const createList = mutation({
  args: { name: v.string() },
  handler: async (ctx, args) => {
    await ctx.db.insert("lists", { ... });
  },
});
```
